The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, May 14: Gold rallied to hit yet another historic high at the bullion market here today on heavy buying from stockists and speculators, supported by an upsurge in global markets. In overseas markets, the yellow metal hit a record high of $1,248.95 in early trade. In Calcutta, 24 carat pure gold rose to Rs 18,625 per 10 gram from Rs 18,410 yesterday.                             
	 Calcutta, May 14: The ATM strike in Bengal on Monday has been deferred for now. The Bengal Provincial Bank Employees Association called off their strike at offsite ATM kiosks of 19 banks after six banks conceded to their demand at a conciliatory meeting convened by the assistant labour commissioner today.                             
	 Mumbai, May 14: Shares of Aban Offshore plunged over 18 per cent on the BSE today after the company said one of its rigs, Aban Pearl, was reported to have sunk in the Caribbean. The scrip sank over 20 per cent to hit a low of Rs 812 before closing at Rs 831.25, down 18.29 per cent.                            
	 New Delhi, May 14: The US administration has named ONGC and Indian Oil among the 41 firms worldwide having energy ties with Iran, an act for which it may impose sanctions on them.                            
	 New Delhi, May 14: People with more than Rs 10 lakh annual income may not get the tax relief proposed in the Direct Taxes Code. Under the first draft, income of Rs 10-25 lakh was to attract tax at 20 per cent, but the final draft may propose 30 per cent tax on income above Rs 10 lakh.                                                                                                                          
